<font face=Arial size=-1 color=black><div class=titlebar>Intro</div>

<div class=itemtext>Although not as sophisticated as its many sequels, Mega Man for NES is a great game, even today.  Most aspects of the game were used in later sequels, though there are a few minor differences between MM1 and the rest of the series.<br><br></div><div class=titlebar>Story</div>

<div class=itemtext>Dr. Light, with his assistant Dr. Wily, has built 8 of the most sophisticated robots in the world - Rock and Roll, general-purpose housekeeping/laboratory robots, Cut Man, the robotic lumberjack, Guts Man, a powerful construction robot who can move boulders, Ice Man, an arctic exploration robot, Fire Man, a garbage disposal robot, Bomb Man, the explosives specialist, and Elec Man, designed to work in a power plant.
<p>Dr. Wily, jealous of Light's fame, shows his true colors, reprogramming 6 of the robots to help him in taking over the world.  He didn't consider Rock and Roll to be powerful enough to be worth stealing.
<p>Rock volunteered to be converted into a fighting robot by Dr. Light.  His design wasn't as tough as that of his industrial counterparts, so he couldn't match them in armor or firepower.  However, he had 2 important advantages.  Since he was designed to work in a chaotic domestic environment or a laboratory, his programming had to be more sophisticated.  He was intelligent enough to expertly dodge his enemies attacks, and versatile enough to allow Dr. Light to outfit him with the now-famous weapon copy system.<br><br></div><div class=titlebar>Unique Features</div>

<div class=itemtext>1.  There are 6 robots instead of 8.<br>
2.  Unlike other NES MM games, the items scattered throughout a level in MM1 will reappear if you lose a 1-up and start part of a level over again.<br>
3.  This is the only MM game with a points system.  There are also small 'dot' items that you can pick up occasionaslly for an extra 1000 points.<br>
4.  Hitting spikes will make you lose a 1-up, even if you have invincibility.<br>
5.  You can pause the game without bringing up the weapon select screen by pressing the select button.  A bug in the game causes an enemy boss' temporary invincibility to run out, even while the game is paused, so it's possible to hit an enemy multiple times with 1 shot.<br><br></div><div class=titlebar>Robots</div>

<div class=itemtext><a href=mm1robots.txt>Official Enemy Names List</a><br><br></div></font></td></tr></table>

