<table BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=70%><tr>
<td VALIGN=TOP bgcolor=ffffff class=itemtable>
<font face=Arial size=-1 color=black><div class=titlebar>Weapons</div>

<div class=itemtext>Thunder Beam<br>
Usefulness: 10<br>
Energy Cost: 1<br>
This is by far the best weapon in MM1.  The Thunder Beam shoots out 3 thunder bolts simultaneously - 1 up, 1 down, and 1 forward.  This weapon covers a very large area and has above average power.  It's definitely the best option for handling screw turrets, suzies (those suction cup blocks that fly back and forth), and other enemies that may attack from overhead.  This weapon can also blow up the large blocks meant for the Power Arm (see below) and send shrapnel flying at enemies.  The Elec Beam actually sort of overshadows the other weapons in the game.  Later sequels (most notably Rockman & Forte, in which all 8 weapons are useful) were designed to have a wider variety of weapons that would each have clear advantages over each other.<br>
Ice Slasher<br>
Usefulness: 8<br>
Energy Cost: 1<br>
The Ice Slasher doesn't usually damage enemies, but rather freezes them so that you can pass by or attack with another weapon.  This makes it extremely useful against the giant hopping cyclops robots that can be found in many of the levels, and other powerful enemies.<br>
Rolling Cutter<br>
Usefulness: 5<br>
Energy Cost: 1<br>
A boomerang-type weapon that has short range and medium firepower and returns to Mega Man.  It's possible to score numerous hits if you time it right, sometimes as many as 4 or 5.  This weapon continues on its path even if it hits an enemy that is temporarily invincible.<br>
Fire Storm<br>
Usefulness: 5<br>
Energy Cost: 1<br>
This weapon fires a wide shot forward, and projects a quick shield of fire that can protect Mega Man from small flying enemies.  It's also quite powerful.<br>
Power Arm<br>
Usefulness: 2<br>
Energy Cost: 2<br>
The Power Arm allows you to pick up large blocks and throw them forward in an arc.  When they hit a wall, they split into a spray of 4 smaller blocks.  It's the most powerful weapon in the game, but there really aren't many large blocks around, except in Cut Man's stage.<br>
Time Bomb<br>
Usefulness: 0<br>
Energy Cost: 2<br>
Probably the least useful weapon in the Mega Man series, the Time Bomb bounces forward slightly ahead of Mega Man, and explodes several seconds later.  MM is not affected by the blast.  It's quite powerful, if you can actually hit something with it.  It can be useful against suzies in some situations, if you're trying to avoid using energy for the Thunder Beam, Fire Storm, or Rolling Cutter.<br><br></div><div class=titlebar>Items</div>

<div class=itemtext>Magnet Beam<br>
Energy Cost: 2<br>
The Magnet Beam is a platform that shoots out in 1-block-wide segments, floating wherever Mega Man's arm cannon points when you press the button.  You can fire a single platform by tapping the button, or a long bridge by holding it.  The shorter the bridge, the longer it stays on screen.  It's generally a good idea to fire 2-3 piece bridges.<br><br></div></font></td></tr></table>

